ARCHITECTURE.md
     1‚Üí# Architecture
     3‚Üí> Document is a work in progress!
     4‚Üí
     5‚Üí‚åòK is born from a simple constraint: can you write a combobox with filtering and sorting using the [compound component](https://kentcdodds.com/blog/compound-components-with-react-hooks) approach? We didn't want to render items manually from an array:
     6‚Üí
     7‚Üí```tsx
     8‚Üí// No
     9‚Üí<>
    10‚Üí  {items.map((item) => {
    11‚Üí    return <div>{item}</div>
    12‚Üí  })}
    13‚Üí</>
    14‚Üí```
    15‚Üí
    16‚ÜíWe didn't want to provide a render prop:
    17‚Üí
    18‚Üí```tsx
    19‚Üí// No
    20‚ÜíonItemRender={({ item }) => {
    21‚Üí  return <div>{item}</div>
    22‚Üí}}
    23‚Üí```
    24‚Üí
    25‚ÜíInstead, we wanted to render components:
    26‚Üí
    27‚Üí```tsx
    28‚Üí// Yes
    29‚Üí<Item>My item</Item>
    30‚Üí```
    31‚Üí
    32‚ÜíEspecially, we wanted full component composition:
    33‚Üí
    34‚Üí```tsx
    35‚Üí// YES
    36‚Üí<>
    37‚Üí  <BlogItems />
    38‚Üí  {staticItems}
    39‚Üí</>
    40‚Üí```
    41‚Üí
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
    46‚Üí## Approach
    48‚Üí‚åòK always keeps every item and group rendered in the React tree. Each item and group adds or removes itself from the DOM based on the search input. The DOM is authoritative.¬ÝItem selection order is based on the DOM order, which is based on the React render order, which the consumer provides.
    49‚Üí
    50‚Üí### Discarded approach
    52‚ÜíWe did not use `React.Children` iteration because it will not support component composition. There is no way to "peek inside" the items contained within `<BlogItems />`, so those items cannot be filtered.
    53‚Üí
    54‚ÜíWe did not use an object-based data array for each item, like `{ name: "Logout", action: () => logout() }` because this is strict and limiting. In reality, the interface of those objects grows with edge-cases, like `image`, `detailedSubTitle`, `hideWhenRootSearch`, etc. We prefer that you have full control of item rendering, including icons, keyboard shortcuts, and styling. Don't want an item shown? Don't render it. Only want to show an item under condition xyz? Render it.
    55‚Üí
    56‚ÜíWe did not use a render prop because they are an inelegant pattern and quickly fall to long, centralised if-else logic chains. For example, if you want a fancy sparkle rainbow item, you need a new if statement to render that item specially.
    57‚Üí
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
    60‚Üí## Example
    62‚Üí```tsx
    63‚Üí<Input value="b" />
    64‚Üí<List>
    65‚Üí  <Item>A</Item>
    66‚Üí  <Item>B</Item>
    67‚Üí</List>
    68‚Üí```
    69‚Üí
    70‚ÜíThe "A" item should not be shown! But we cannot remove it from the React tree, because the user controls it. In most cases, this is easy because the rendered items is sourced from a backing data array:
    71‚Üí
    72‚Üí```tsx
    73‚Üí<>
    74‚Üí  {['A', 'B'].map((item) => {
    75‚Üí    if (matches(item, search)) {
    76‚Üí      return <Item>{item}</Item>
    77‚Üí    }
    78‚Üí  })}
    79‚Üí</>
    80‚Üí```
    81‚Üí
    82‚ÜíBut in our case, the item will remain in the React tree and just be removed from the DOM:
    83‚Üí
    84‚Üí```tsx
    85‚Üí<List>
    86‚Üí  {/* returns `null`, no DOM created */}
    87‚Üí  <Item>A</Item>
    88‚Üí  <Item>B</Item>
    89‚Üí</List>
    90‚Üí```
    91‚Üí
    92‚Üí## Performance
    94‚ÜíThis is more expensive memory wise, because if there are 2,000 items but the list is filtered to only 2 items, we still allocate memory for 2,000 instances of the Item component. But it's our only option! Thankfully we can still keep the DOM size to 2 items.
    95‚Üí
    96‚Üí## Groups
    98‚ÜíItem mount informs both the root and the parent group, which keeps track of items within it. Each group informs the root.
README.md
     5‚Üí# ‚åòK
     7‚Üí‚åòK is a command menu React component that can also be used as an accessible combobox. You render items, it filters and sorts them automatically. ‚åòK supports a fully composable API <sup><sup>[How?](/ARCHITECTURE.md)</sup></sup>, so you can wrap items in other components or even as static JSX.
     8‚Üí
     9‚Üí## Install
    11‚Üí```bash
    12‚Üípnpm install cmdk
    13‚Üí```
    14‚Üí
    15‚Üí## Use
    17‚Üí```tsx
    18‚Üíimport { Command } from 'cmdk'
    19‚Üí
    20‚Üíconst CommandMenu = () => {
    21‚Üí  return (
    22‚Üí    <Command label="Command Menu">
    23‚Üí      <Command.Input />
    24‚Üí      <Command.List>
    25‚Üí        <Command.Empty>No results found.</Command.Empty>
    26‚Üí
    27‚Üí        <Command.Group heading="Letters">
    28‚Üí          <Command.Item>a</Command.Item>
    29‚Üí          <Command.Item>b</Command.Item>
    30‚Üí          <Command.Separator />
    31‚Üí          <Command.Item>c</Command.Item>
    32‚Üí        </Command.Group>
    33‚Üí
    34‚Üí        <Command.Item>Apple</Command.Item>
    35‚Üí      </Command.List>
    36‚Üí    </Command>
    37‚Üí  )
    38‚Üí}
    39‚Üí```
    40‚Üí
    41‚ÜíOr in a dialog:
    42‚Üí
    43‚Üí```tsx
    44‚Üíimport { Command } from 'cmdk'
    45‚Üí
    46‚Üíconst CommandMenu = () => {
    47‚Üí  const [open, setOpen] = React.useState(false)
    48‚Üí
    49‚Üí  // Toggle the menu when ‚åòK is pressed
    50‚Üí  React.useEffect(() => {
    51‚Üí    const down = (e) => {
    52‚Üí      if (e.key === 'k' && (e.metaKey || e.ctrlKey)) {
    53‚Üí        e.preventDefault()
    54‚Üí        setOpen((open) => !open)
    55‚Üí      }
    56‚Üí    }
    57‚Üí
    58‚Üí    document.addEventListener('keydown', down)
    59‚Üí    return () => document.removeEventListener('keydown', down)
    60‚Üí  }, [])
    61‚Üí
    62‚Üí  return (
    63‚Üí    <Command.Dialog open={open} onOpenChange={setOpen} label="Global Command Menu">
    64‚Üí      <Command.Input />
    65‚Üí      <Command.List>
    66‚Üí        <Command.Empty>No results found.</Command.Empty>
    67‚Üí
    68‚Üí        <Command.Group heading="Letters">
    69‚Üí          <Command.Item>a</Command.Item>
    70‚Üí          <Command.Item>b</Command.Item>
    71‚Üí          <Command.Separator />
    72‚Üí          <Command.Item>c</Command.Item>
    73‚Üí        </Command.Group>
    74‚Üí
    75‚Üí        <Command.Item>Apple</Command.Item>
    76‚Üí      </Command.List>
    77‚Üí    </Command.Dialog>
    78‚Üí  )
    79‚Üí}
    80‚Üí```
    81‚Üí
    82‚Üí## Parts and styling
    84‚ÜíAll parts forward props, including `ref`, to an appropriate element. Each part has a specific data-attribute (starting with `cmdk-`) that can be used for styling.
    85‚Üí
    86‚Üí### Command `[cmdk-root]`
    88‚ÜíRender this to show the command menu inline, or use [Dialog](#dialog-cmdk-dialog-cmdk-overlay) to render in a elevated context. Can be controlled with the `value` and `onValueChange` props.
    89‚Üí
    90‚Üí> **Note**
    91‚Üí>
    92‚Üí> Values are always trimmed with the [trim()](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/String/trim) method.
    93‚Üí
    94‚Üí```tsx
    95‚Üíconst [value, setValue] = React.useState('apple')
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   153‚Üí### Dialog `[cmdk-dialog]` `[cmdk-overlay]`
   155‚ÜíProps are forwarded to [Command](#command-cmdk-root). Composes Radix UI's Dialog component. The overlay is always rendered. See the [Radix Documentation](https://www.radix-ui.com/docs/primitives/components/dialog) for more information. Can be controlled with the `open` and `onOpenChange` props.
   156‚Üí
   157‚Üí```tsx
   158‚Üíconst [open, setOpen] = React.useState(false)
   159‚Üí
   160‚Üíreturn (
   161‚Üí  <Command.Dialog open={open} onOpenChange={setOpen}>
   162‚Üí    ...
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   180‚Üí### Input `[cmdk-input]`
   182‚ÜíAll props are forwarded to the underlying `input` element. Can be controlled with the `value` and `onValueChange` props.
   183‚Üí
   184‚Üí```tsx
   185‚Üíconst [search, setSearch] = React.useState('')
   186‚Üí
   187‚Üíreturn <Command.Input value={search} onValueChange={setSearch} />
   188‚Üí```
   189‚Üí
   190‚Üí### List `[cmdk-list]`
   192‚ÜíContains items and groups. Animate height using the `--cmdk-list-height` CSS variable.
   193‚Üí
   194‚Üí```css
   195‚Üí[cmdk-list] {
   196‚Üí  min-height: 300px;
   197‚Üí  height: var(--cmdk-list-height);
   198‚Üí  max-height: 500px;
   199‚Üí  transition: height 100ms ease;
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   212‚Üí### Item `[cmdk-item]` `[data-disabled?]` `[data-selected?]`
   214‚ÜíItem that becomes active on pointer enter. You should provide a unique `value` for each item, but it will be automatically inferred from the `.textContent`.
   215‚Üí
   216‚Üí```tsx
   217‚Üí<Command.Item
   218‚Üí  onSelect={(value) => console.log('Selected', value)}
   219‚Üí  // Value is implicity "apple" because of the provided text content
   220‚Üí>
   221‚Üí  Apple
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   242‚Üí### Group `[cmdk-group]` `[hidden?]`
   244‚ÜíGroups items together with the given `heading` (`[cmdk-group-heading]`).
   245‚Üí
   246‚Üí```tsx
   247‚Üí<Command.Group heading="Fruit">
   248‚Üí  <Command.Item>Apple</Command.Item>
   249‚Üí</Command.Group>
   250‚Üí```
   251‚Üí
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   256‚Üí### Separator `[cmdk-separator]`
   258‚ÜíVisible when the search query is empty or `alwaysRender` is true, hidden otherwise.
   259‚Üí
   260‚Üí### Empty `[cmdk-empty]`
   262‚ÜíAutomatically renders when there are no results for the search query.
   263‚Üí
   264‚Üí### Loading `[cmdk-loading]`
   266‚ÜíYou should conditionally render this with `progress` while loading asynchronous items.
   267‚Üí
   268‚Üí```tsx
   269‚Üíconst [loading, setLoading] = React.useState(false)
   270‚Üí
   271‚Üíreturn <Command.List>{loading && <Command.Loading>Hang on‚Ä¶</Command.Loading>}</Command.List>
   272‚Üí```
   273‚Üí
   274‚Üí### `useCommandState(state => state.selectedField)`
   276‚ÜíHook that composes [`useSyncExternalStore`](https://reactjs.org/docs/hooks-reference.html#usesyncexternalstore). Pass a function that returns a slice of the command menu state to re-render when that slice changes. This hook is provided for advanced use cases and should not be commonly used.
   277‚Üí
   278‚ÜíA good use case would be to render a more detailed empty state, like so:
   279‚Üí
   280‚Üí```tsx
   281‚Üíconst search = useCommandState((state) => state.search)
   282‚Üíreturn <Command.Empty>No results found for "{search}".</Command.Empty>
   283‚Üí```
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   285‚Üí## Examples
   287‚ÜíCode snippets for common use cases.
   288‚Üí
   289‚Üí### Nested items
   291‚ÜíOften selecting one item should navigate deeper, with a more refined set of items. For example selecting "Change theme‚Ä¶" should show new items "Dark theme" and "Light theme". We call these sets of items "pages", and they can be implemented with simple state:
   292‚Üí
   293‚Üí```tsx
   294‚Üíconst ref = React.useRef(null)
   295‚Üíconst [open, setOpen] = React.useState(false)
   296‚Üíconst [search, setSearch] = React.useState('')
   297‚Üíconst [pages, setPages] = React.useState([])
   298‚Üíconst page = pages[pages.length - 1]
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   338‚Üí### Show sub-items when searching
   340‚ÜíIf your items have nested sub-items that you only want to reveal when searching, render based on the search state:
   341‚Üí
   342‚Üí```tsx
   343‚Üíconst SubItem = (props) => {
   344‚Üí  const search = useCommandState((state) => state.search)
   345‚Üí  if (!search) return null
   346‚Üí  return <Command.Item {...props} />
   347‚Üí}
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
