     3‚Üí## Getting Started
     5‚ÜíFirst, run the development server:
     6‚Üí
     7‚Üí```bash
     8‚Üípnpm run dev
     9‚Üí```
    10‚Üí
    11‚ÜíOpen [http://localhost:3000](http://localhost:3000) with your browser to see the result.
    12‚Üí
    13‚ÜíYou can start editing the page by modifying `pages/index.tsx`. The page auto-updates as you edit the file.
    14‚Üí
    15‚Üí[API routes](https://nextjs.org/docs/api-routes/introduction) can be accessed on [http://localhost:3000/api/hello](http://localhost:3000/api/hello). This endpoint can be edited in `pages/api/hello.ts`.
    16‚Üí
    17‚ÜíThe `pages/api` directory is mapped to `/api/*`. Files in this directory are treated as [API routes](https://nextjs.org/docs/api-routes/introduction) instead of React pages.
    18‚Üí
    19‚Üí## Learn More
    21‚ÜíTo learn more about Next.js, take a look at the following resources:
    22‚Üí
    23‚Üí- [Next.js Documentation](https://nextjs.org/docs) - learn about Next.js features and API.
    24‚Üí- [Learn Next.js](https://nextjs.org/learn) - an interactive Next.js tutorial.
    25‚Üí
    26‚ÜíYou can check out [the Next.js GitHub repository](https://github.com/vercel/next.js/) - your feedback and contributions are welcome!
    27‚Üí
    28‚Üí## Deploy on Vercel
    30‚ÜíThe easiest way to deploy your Next.js app is to use the [Vercel Platform](https://vercel.com/new?utm_medium=default-template&filter=next.js&utm_source=create-next-app&utm_campaign=create-next-app-readme) from the creators of Next.js.
